# Finance Management Module — LDM College ERP

Small-college design (≤60 users). Simple, practical, maintainable.

---

## 1. Database Schema

Four Mongoose models. No calculated fields stored; all computed at query time.

---

### 1.1 `FeeStructure` — Define what a student owes

```ts
{
  program: ObjectId → Program,   // e.g., DMLT
  session: ObjectId → Session,   // e.g., 2024-2025
  semester: Number,              // 1, 2, ...
  total_amount: Number,          // e.g., 25000 (rupees)
  due_date: Date,
  description: String,           // "Sem 1 Tuition Fee"
  is_active: Boolean,
  createdAt, updatedAt           // timestamps: true
}
```

---

### 1.2 `FeePayment` — Track what a student actually paid

```ts
{
  student: ObjectId → User,      // role: 'student'
  fee_structure: ObjectId → FeeStructure,
  amount_paid: Number,           // cumulative total paid so far
  payments: [                    // array of individual transactions
    {
      amount: Number,
      paid_on: Date,
      mode: 'cash' | 'online' | 'cheque' | 'DD',
      receipt_no: String,        // manually assigned
      remarks: String,
      recorded_by: ObjectId → User (admin)
    }
  ],
  status: 'unpaid' | 'partial' | 'paid',  // computed + stored for fast lookup
  createdAt, updatedAt
}
```

> **Status rule** (recalculate on every payment update):
> - `amount_paid === 0` → `unpaid`
> - `amount_paid < total_amount` → `partial`
> - `amount_paid >= total_amount` → `paid`

---

### 1.3 `Expense` — College operating expenses

```ts
{
  title: String,                 // "Electricity Bill"
  amount: Number,
  category: 'utilities' | 'maintenance' | 'supplies' | 'events' | 'other',
  paid_on: Date,
  paid_to: String,               // vendor/person name
  remarks: String,
  recorded_by: ObjectId → User (admin),
  createdAt, updatedAt
}
```

---

### 1.4 `Salary` — Staff salary records (monthly)

```ts
{
  employee: ObjectId → User,     // role: 'teacher' | 'employee'
  month: String,                 // "2025-01" (YYYY-MM)
  base_amount: Number,
  deductions: Number,            // default 0
  net_amount: Number,            // computed: base - deductions (stored for record)
  status: 'pending' | 'paid',
  paid_on: Date,                 // null if pending
  paid_by: ObjectId → User (admin),
  remarks: String,
  createdAt, updatedAt
}
```

> `net_amount` is stored (not computed) because it is a **historical financial record** — the base salary may change later.

---

## 2. Business Logic

### 2.1 Fee Payment Flow

```
Admin opens Student → Payment
      ↓
Select FeeStructure (program + session + semester)
      ↓
If no FeePayment exists → create one with amount_paid: 0
      ↓
Admin enters payment amount + mode + receipt_no
      ↓
Push to payments[] array
Recalculate amount_paid = sum(payments[].amount)
Update status: unpaid / partial / paid
      ↓
Save FeePayment document
```

**Remaining balance** (never stored, always computed):
```
remaining = fee_structure.total_amount - fee_payment.amount_paid
```

**Overpayment rule:** Reject if `new amount + amount_paid > total_amount`. Show clear error.

---

### 2.2 Expense Flow

```
Admin → Add Expense
      Enter: title, amount, category, paid_on, paid_to
      Save → Expense document created
```

No approval workflow needed for a 60-user system. Admin is sole authority.

---

### 2.3 Salary Flow

```
Each month:
Admin → Add Salary Record for each employee
      Enter: base_amount, deductions, month
      net_amount = base - deductions → stored
      status: 'pending'
      
When paid:
Admin → Mark as Paid
      status → 'paid'
      paid_on → today's date
```

---

### 2.4 Finance Dashboard Calculations

All aggregated at query time. No pre-computed totals stored.

```
Total Revenue   = SUM(FeePayment.amount_paid) for current session
Total Expenses  = SUM(Expense.amount) + SUM(Salary.net_amount WHERE status='paid')
Net Balance     = Total Revenue - Total Expenses
Pending Fees    = SUM(FeeStructure.total_amount - FeePayment.amount_paid) for status != 'paid'
Pending Salary  = SUM(Salary.net_amount WHERE status='pending')
```

